  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Strengthening the Local Production of Essential Medicines in Developing Countries through Advisory &amp; Capacity-Building Support - Phase 5.2</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Related to 120117 - Phase 5.2: This project will continue and expand UNIDO work rendered in support of the local production of essential generic medicines in developing and least developed countries (DCs/LDCs) that began with funding from Germany in January 2006. Phase 5 started in 2014 with a budget of EUR 700,000 for a two-year period (2014-15) yet based on a September 2014 offer of additional donor funding over the same amount (EUR 700,000) will be expanded and extended until end-2016.

Substantively, the project will build on the progress and results of the past, notably the milestone achievement in phases 3 &amp; 4 following UNIDO&#x2019;s entering into a partnership with the African Union Commission (AUC) in July 2011. The partnership culminated in the joint preparation and formal adoption at highest AU policy levels (AU Conference of Ministers of Health, AU Heads of State and Government Summit) of a &#x201C;Business Plan&#x201D; (BP) for the accelerated implementation of the 2007 AU Pharmaceutical Manufacturing Plan for Africa (PMPA) in mid-2012. Owned by the AU, the PMPA BP has become the main reference document for action in support of LPP in Africa in the years ahead. UNIDO is the AUC&#x2019;s lead partner in the implementation of the PMPA BP and has been driving the early work towards the formation of a nucleus of partners. These partners (among others: WHO and UNAIDS) have begun collaborating on early implementation of the Business Plan in Ghana, using the national strategy developed by UNIDO in previous phases of the project as the template.

In addition, since late 2013 UNIDO, UNAIDS and WHO have stepped up efforts to collaborate in supporting the implementation of the PMPA Business Plan at large, culminating in a Heads of Agency meeting in Geneva in June 2014. It was agreed that UNIDO would play the lead role in working with, and coordinate the activities of, the partners to accelerate progress towards full implementation which in turn implied a need for dedicated resources. This position was further endorsed by the UNIDO Executive Board on 4 July 2014.
Therefore, in addition to the continuation, deepening and roll-out of UNIDO interventions, the present proposal incorporates a UNIDO cost-sharing contribution of EUR 140,000 &#x2013; amounting to ten percent of the German-funded phase 5 total (EUR 1.4million) &#x2013; that enables UNIDO to continue to lead the start-up phase of the BP&#x2019;s implementation in collaboration with the AUC.
Advisory and capacity-building interventions will be geared to improving the operating environment of pharmaceutical manufacturers and thus address key constraints at policy and institutional levels. Specifically, the main planned activity clusters comprise the following:
o Continue to support the implementation of select dimensions of the pharmaceutical manufacturing sector strategies that were developed and agreed by national stakeholders in earlier project phases in Kenya and Ghana;
o Kick-start the implementation of the Kenya GMP Roadmap (GIZ Grant);
o Further strengthen the Southern African Generics Medicines Association (SAGMA) on its way to self-sufficiency; support the newly founded pan-African apex body (Federation of African Pharmaceutical Manufacturers Associations/FAPMA) during start-up and scale up;
o Support the Federation of East African Pharmaceutical Manufacturers (FEAPM) in conducting an Internship Academy (GIZ Grant);
o Support the African Vaccines Manufacturers Initiative (AVMI) in assessing the feasibility of vaccines production at the continental level and at the national level in Senegal (GIZ Grant);
o Continue and expand the support to St Luke Foundation (UR Tanzania) in delivering modular training courses on industrial pharmacy to a Master&#x2019;s Degree;
o Apply the GMP Roadmap as central tool (solution package) that has been designed to support further pharma sector development interventions, both within PMPA BP implementation and without;
o Develop training modules on pharmaceutical company upgrading, specifically on (i) capital project lifecycle management and ii) achieving operational efficiencies (operational excellence);
o Conduct value chain analysis on pharmaceutical manufacturing in the EAC region (GIZ Grant);
o Support the early PMPA BP implementation in three ways: (i) Elaborate a detailed TC programme to guide the further preparation of a multi-year, multi-party support intervention, including appropriate institutional, management and implementation structures; (ii) Engage in resource mobilisation to ensure broader and longer-term implementation assistance; and (iii) Collaborate with the nucleus of partners in early implementation of the Business Plan in Ghana.

Africa will remain the main regional focus for the project given that this is where the access to drugs crisis is most profound, where there is substantial political interest in the area, and where the previous projects have gained the most experience.</narrative>
